# Concepts Clarification — Event Ticketing Platform

---

## QUESTION 1 — API Types: What Are They, Why REST, How They Work

---

### What Is an API?

An API (Application Programming Interface) is simply **a contract between two programs** on how they talk to each other.  
Your frontend (Next.js) needs to get event data from your backend (Spring Boot). The API is how they do that — it defines: "send a GET request to `/api/events`, and I'll send you back a JSON list of events."

---

### The 3 Main API Types

| Type | Full Name | How it works | Best For |
|------|-----------|-------------|---------|
| **REST** | Representational State Transfer | You send HTTP verbs (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) to URLs. Each URL = one resource. | CRUD apps, public APIs, mobile apps |
| **GraphQL** | Graph Query Language | Client sends a "what I need" query in one request. Server returns exactly that shape. | Complex frontends needing custom data shapes |
| **WebSocket** | — | Persistent two-way connection. Server can push data without client asking. | Live chat, live scores, real-time notifications |

---

### Why REST Was the Right Choice for Your Project

Your project chose **REST** — here's why it's specifically correct for you:

**1. Your data is structured around resources**
Every endpoint maps cleanly to a thing:
- `/api/events` → events
- `/api/bookings` → bookings
- `/api/payments` → payments

REST was literally designed for this. One URL = one resource. This matches your domain perfectly.

**2. Spring Boot makes REST trivial**
`@RestController`, `@GetMapping`, `@PostMapping` — these are first-class Spring Boot annotations. You get REST out of the box.

**3. Stripe's webhook IS REST**
Stripe sends a `POST` to your `/api/webhooks/stripe`. This is REST. Your API style must match what Stripe sends.

**4. Next.js consumes REST naturally**
Your frontend uses React Query + Axios. Both are built for REST. You'd need extra libraries and complexity for GraphQL.

**5. You don't need real-time (mostly)**
WebSocket is for things like live auction bidding. Your use case: user searches events, books a ticket, pays. This is request-response — REST.

> **The exception:** Later if you add "live seat availability updates" on the booking UI, you'd add a WebSocket layer on top of REST — not replace REST.

---

### How REST Works in Your Project (End-to-End)

```
USER BROWSER
  │  clicks "Book Now"
  ▼
NEXT.JS (Vercel)
  │  Axios sends: POST https://api.ticketing.com/api/bookings
  │  Headers: Authorization: Bearer {JWT token}
  │  Body: { tierId: 5, quantity: 2 }
  ▼
SPRING BOOT (Railway)
  │  JwtFilter validates the JWT → extracts userId
  │  @PostMapping("/api/bookings") → BookingController.reserveTickets()
  │  BookingService:
  │    └─ Acquire Redis lock (tier:5:user:99)
  │    └─ Re-check availability INSIDE lock (TOCTOU fix)
  │    └─ Lua script decrements Redis count
  │    └─ Creates Booking entity (state=RESERVED)
  │    └─ Sets expires_at = now + 5 minutes
  │  Returns: HTTP 201 { bookingId: 123, expiresAt: "...", status: "RESERVED" }
  ▼
NEXT.JS
  displays: "Booking reserved! Complete payment in 4:59"
```

---

### Your API Structure (All Domains)

```
POST   /api/auth/register          → create user account
POST   /api/auth/login             → get JWT token

GET    /api/events                 → paginated event list
POST   /api/events                 → create event (ORGANIZER only)
GET    /api/events/{id}            → single event with venue + tiers
PUT    /api/events/{id}            → update event
POST   /api/events/{id}/publish    → change status to PUBLISHED

POST   /api/bookings               → reserve seats → returns booking
GET    /api/bookings/{id}          → booking details + QR code
POST   /api/bookings/{id}/checkout → create Stripe session → returns URL
POST   /api/bookings/{id}/check-in → mark attended (ORGANIZER only)

POST   /api/webhooks/stripe        → Stripe calls this after payment

GET    /api/search/events?q=&city= → filtered event search
```

